\begin_layout Standard
Running through the middle of the continent of Australia is often a ridge
 of high pressure called the subtropical ridge (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Gallant-SE-Aus-Teleconnetions"

\end_inset

).
 The subtropical ridge is responsible for largely fine and sunny weather
 to regions beneath it and is associated with the descending branch of the
 Hadley cell (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Sturman2005"

\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Sinclair1996"

\end_inset

 studied the climatology of such high pressure systems and their prevalence
 in the southern hemisphere.
 The author found that there tended to be a wintertime maximum in anticyclonic
 distribution over the Great Australian Bight.
 The anticyclones from the Bight then tend to migrate north-eastward over
 the Australian continent.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Sinclair1996"

\end_inset

 also found that high pressure systems often migrated quicker in summer,
 while there were large numbers of anticyclones in the Tasman Sea for most
 of the year.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Tasman Sea, south west of New Zealand, is also a common location
 for so-called ‘blocking highs’.
 Blocking highs are said to be long-lived high pressure systems (lasting
 for more than about 5 days) that are associated with an anomalous breakdown
 in the prevailing westerly flow (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "Sinclair1996"

\end_inset

).
 The decay of the blocking high can also be followed by a re-intensification
 shortly thereafter (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "Sinclair1996"

\end_inset

).
 According to geostrophic theory such blocking highs in the Tasman Sea would
 likely produce prolonged periods of onshore flow for eastern/south eastern
 Australia (although ridging of high pressure from the blocking centre could
 indicate stable conditions over much of the eastern and central Australian
 continent instead).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tendencies of high pressure systems over Australia was also more recently
 examined using a Self-Organising Map (SOM) by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Alexander2010"

\end_inset

.
 Figure 2 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Alexander2010"

\end_inset

, which uses ERA-40 reanalysis from 1958-2001, clearly depicts the subtropical
 ridge of high pressure, as well as the maximum in system density through
 the Great Australian Bight (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Alexander-SOM"

\end_inset

).
 Further evidence is thus provided to suggest that large sections of the
 Australian continent are commonly under the influence of high pressure
 systems, and that consequently there is dominant stable weather regime
 for the Australian region.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The more unstable regimes common to the Australian region are normally linked
 to the passage of low pressure systems and associated cold fronts or troughs.
 In terms of wind speed, the unstable regimes are potentially more advantageous
 for the production of wind energy as low pressure systems are inherently
 associated with higher wind speeds.
 In Australia there are two main types of low pressure systems that affect
 the weather: tropical and extra-tropical or mid-latitude cyclones (although
 transitions between the two types are not uncommon (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Pezza2008"

\end_inset

)).
 Tropical systems are normally associated with the Inter-Tropical Convergence
 Zone (ITCZ) and form in bands either side of the convergence zone where
 factors including low Coriolis force and vertical wind shear are favourable
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Sturman2005"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With respect to the Australian region, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hassim2008"

\end_inset

 have studied trends in tropical cyclones using BoM best track data.
 The authors found that for the period 1970-2005 there was a steady decline
 in total cyclone numbers off the east coast of Australia, while off the
 west coast no significant trend was visible.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hassim2008"

\end_inset

 also found statistically significant downward trends in minimum central
 pressure (likely to be due to an increased occurrence of the more severe
 (category 4 and 5) storms).
 The potential for useful energy to be produced from locations under the
 influence of tropical cyclones is questionable though as, in particular,
 wind turbines are shut down at wind speeds beyond about 25 ms
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
-1
\end_layout

\end_inset

, while wind speeds beyond 35 ms
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
-1
\end_layout

\end_inset

 would likely result in damage.
 Solar irradiance is also likely to be negatively impacted by the presence
 of large-scale convection and cloud formation associated with topical storms.
 In the northern regions of Australia heat lows, which form as a result
 of continental heating, are also common in summer (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Simmonds2000"

\end_inset

).
 However, heat lows generally do not have as large a pressure gradient as
 tropical cyclones (a proxy for wind speed) (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Simmonds2000"

\end_inset

), which most likely means their significance in terms of providing useful
 wind power is limited.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other more common type of cyclone likely to affect wind speed and solar
 irradiance in Australia is the extratropical cyclone.
 Extratropical cyclones that affect the Australian continent are commonly
 linked to the southern hemisphere storm track, which was extensively studied
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Trenberth1991"

\end_inset

 using European Centre for Medium-range Weather Forecasting (ECMWF) reanalysis
 data.
 Closely related to meridional temperature gradients, the southern hemisphere
 storm track is stronger in summer than winter but is always close to 50°S
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Trenberth1991"

\end_inset

).
 In winter there tends to be a broader storm track (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Trenberth1991"

\end_inset

) indicating a higher likelihood (when compared to summer) that cyclones
 from the storm track will reach the southern part of the Australian continent
 during this time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to the study of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Trenberth1991"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jones1993"

\end_inset

 have shown very similar cyclone characteristics using data from the BoM
 in conjunction with an automated cyclone tracking scheme.
 The authors found that the Australian continent is dominated by heat lows
 and tropical lows during summer, while in winter and spring there tended
 to be a transition to higher occurrences of extratropical cyclones.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jones1993"

\end_inset

 also suggested that the traditional position for blocking highs in summer
 through the Tasman Sea is often replaced by extratropical cyclones in winter.
 In a follow-up study to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jones1993"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Simmonds2000"

\end_inset

 used NCEP-NCAR reanalysis and the Melbourne University cyclone tracking
 scheme to study the behaviour of extratropical cyclones in the southern
 hemisphere.
 Qualitatively similar to that of the 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jones1993"

\end_inset

 study, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Simmonds2000"

\end_inset

 also found the position of maximum cyclone density to lie between 50º-70ºS,
 depending on season.
 Quantitatively though, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Simmonds2000"

\end_inset

 found double the amount of cyclones as previous studies (like 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Jones1993"

\end_inset

), noted as being due to higher resolution data.
 Given then, the numerous studies all suggesting a storm track or cyclone
 density maximum at about 50º-60ºS, it is not surprising that there exist
 studies proposing a significant synoptic mode of variability in this region.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Commonly referred to as SAM, the Southern Annular Mode describes a large
 portion of the variability in sea-level pressure for the southern hemisphere.
 Depicted in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Thompson2000"

\end_inset

 as being the first Empirical Orthogonal Function (EOF-1) of the lower-troposphe
ric geopotential height fields, SAM also manifests in the wind field.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Watterson2007"

\end_inset

 presented the existence of such a SAM-like mode in the wind by using vertically
 integrated zonal winds, simulated from 1871-1970 by the Commonwealth Scientific
 and Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) mk3 model.
 Labeled as a high-latitude mode, EOF-1 of the monthly mean vertically integrate
d zonal wind showed a distinct peak at about 60ºS which explained 53% of
 the monthly variance; suggesting a close association with the previously
 defined storm track (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Watterson2007"

\end_inset

).
 The structure of the high-latitude mode was also seen to be quite annular
 (matching the annularity suggested by SAM).
 EOF-2 (which explained 22% of the monthly variance) was shown not to be
 significantly annular at all, but rather, more closely linked to the subtropica
l jet (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Watterson2007"

\end_inset

).
 In accordance with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Watterson2007"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Iijima2009"

\end_inset

 showed sea-surface wind data from the QuikSCAT satellite that seemed to
 match the wind patterns suggested by SAM.
 
