\begin_layout Section
Covariance of Wind Speed and Solar Irradiance over Australia
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Lit-Cov-Wind-Solar"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There does not appear to be any study in the literature that directly compares
 wind speed and solar radiation variability over Australia.
 Even when considering investigations into only wind speed or only solar
 radiation variability the depth of research is still poor.
 Thus an insight into the covariance between wind speed and solar radiation
 from the literature is only possible by comparing the general characteristics
 found from research into each variable separately.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Somewhat unexpectedly, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Lyons1989"

\end_inset

 observed that instances of high pressure ridging directly above south-west
 WA were the second most influential synoptic state for positive wind power
 production in Perth.
 Yet in general terms anticyclones are the bearer of fine weather and light
 winds.
 Therefore, one conclusion that could be made from the work of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Lyons1989"

\end_inset

 is that under the influence of a ridging anticyclone coastal regions can
 have a positive covariance between wind speed and solar irradiance (or
 rather, that sunny conditions can coincide with windy conditions).
 This type of positive covariance could be advantageous for hybrid energy
 system.
 For instance, an hybrid system exposed to a sunny and windy day could disperse
 excess energy into nighttime hours if it incorporated storage.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In terms of the findings from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Lyons1989"

\end_inset

, one can also conclude that determinations of wind speed based purely from
 knowledge of the distribution of pressure are not necessarily very accurate.
 Knowledge of the local conditions in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Lyons1989"

\end_inset

 brought about a better understanding of wind speed variability which most
 likely would have been missed by a simple analysis of the large scale forcing.
 Thus one could argue that any conclusions made from analysis of the pressure
 fields must be qualified by noting the potential influence of local effects.
 However, the altering of wind speeds by local conditions like the sea-breeze
 is likely to be less relevant for locations away from an anticyclonic centre
 (where geostrophic forcing is greater).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering the works of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jones1993"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Simmonds2000"

\end_inset

 there should be extratropical cyclones that, particularly in winter-time,
 will be influencing atmospheric conditions in the southern latitudes of
 Australia.
 For example, the southern regions of Australia (~29-44ºS) have a typical
 cyclone density of close to one cyclone for the whole region during both
 summer and winter (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Jones1993"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Simmonds2000"

\end_inset

).
 In terms of the northern regions of Australia, cyclone system densities
 (most likely tropical and thermal systems) commonly exceed double that
 of the southern regions (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Jones1993"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Simmonds2000"

\end_inset

).
 Given then that the low pressure centres are usually associated with cold
 fronts or troughs and bands of convection it is likely that there would
 be relatively high winds and below average levels of DSR, during each of
 the cyclonic events mentioned above--indicating the strong possibility
 for a negative covariance to exist between wind speed and solar irradiance
 for regions under the influence of such cyclonic systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Analysing some of the literature into the potential synoptic influences
 on wind speed and solar irradiance suggests that anticyclonic regimes may
 be responsible for driving both a positive and negative covariance between
 wind speed and solar irradiance, while cyclonic regimes are most likely
 responsible for a negative covariance.
 Under anticyclonic regimes, coastal regions may experience both sunny weather
 and relatively high wind speeds due to local effects and that such a covariance
 could be advantageous to a hybrid energy system as neither resource is
 likely to be at a minimum at the same time (assuming day time conditions).
 However, this analysis of some of the literature is far from being quantitative
ly robust.
 A more comprehensive study would still be needed in order to quantify the
 general covariance of wind speed and solar irradiance over Australia; enabling
 the determination of the likely effects on renewable energy production.
 
\end_layout

